en. This past year, we accomplished A LOT, thanks to the hard work of our team and continuous support from our users like you. I want to take a few minutes to do a quick recap of all the things that [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com/wpforms-turns-3/">WPForms Turns 3 Years Old &#8211; Bonus Prizes + What&#8217;s New &#038; What&#8217;s Coming Next</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com">WPForms</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11:"Syed Balkhi";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:14015:"<p>WPForms is officially three years old, and wow what an incredible journey it has been.</p>\n<p>This past year, we accomplished A LOT, thanks to the hard work of our team and continuous support from our users like you.</p>\n<p>I want to take a few minutes to do a quick recap of all the things that happened this past year, share what&#8217;s coming next, and celebrate with a huge giveaway!</p>\n<h3>Fun Third-Year Stats for WPForms</h3>\n<p>WPForms has come a long way in the past 12 months. Here are some fun stats to celebrate our third year.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>WPForms is now the <strong>19th most popular WordPress plugin</strong> of all time with over 1,000,000 active installs (very soon it&#8217;ll pass the 2 million mark).</li>\n<li>We have continued to maintain a <strong>4.9 out of 5 star</strong> rating average with over <a href="https://wpforms.com/user-reviews/" title="WPForms User Reviews">3600+ five-star ratings</a>.</li>\n<li>We officially translated WPForms into 4 new languages (German, Spanish, Italian, and Japanese). More translations are coming as we continue our global expansion.</li>\n<li>We added over <a href="https://wpforms.com/blog/" title="WPForms Blog">90+ new blog posts</a> and <a href="https://wpforms.com/docs/" title="WPForms Documentation">64+ new documentation</a> to help you succeed with WPForms.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Although it&#8217;s not a stat, but we now have brand swag (shirt + stickers), and yes you can get one for free.</p>\n<h3>WPForms Birthday Giveaway</h3>\n<p>We want to send this awesome WPForms T-Shirt + Stickers to the first 150 users who share their WPForms story.</p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpformstshirt.png" alt="WPForms T-Shirt + Stickers" width="620" height="617" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-427881" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpformstshirt.png 620w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpformstshirt-150x150.png 150w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpformstshirt-300x300.png 300w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpformstshirt-100x100.png 100w" sizes="(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px" /></p>\n<p>All you have to do is share your WPForms story in a quick video and then leave us a comment on this blog post sharing your favorite WPForms feature. </p>\n<p>Don&#8217;t worry, you don&#8217;t need a fancy camera equipment to record a video testimonial. We just want to hear your story and better connect with you.</p>\n<p>That&#8217;s why we have made it super easy to record and upload your video testimonial.</p>\n<p><strong>Method 1. Use your laptop camera to record your video</strong></p>\n<p>Simply open the link below, and you will be able to use your laptop camera to record and upload your video testimonial.</p>\n<p><a class="btn btn-block" style="background-color: #659a17 !important; color: #fff !important; padding: 20px 25px !important; text-align: center; text-decoration: none; border-radius: 4px !important; -moz-border-radius: 4px !important; -webkit-border-radius: 4px !important; line-height: 48px; font-weight: bold;" title="Click here to join our affiliate program" href="https://secure.boast.io/site/kudos/WPFORMS" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Click here to Share Your WPForms Story</a></p>\n<p><strong>Method 2. Use your Smart Phone to record a short video</strong></p>\n<p>We&#8217;re using Boast.io to collect video testimonials. You can download the Boast app on your <a href="https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/boast.io/id860833000" title="Boast App for iPhone" rel="noopener nofollow" target="_blank">iPhone</a> or <a href="https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=io.boast" title="Boast Google Play App" rel="noopener nofollow" target="_blank">Android Phone</a>, and then type the campaign code: <strong>WPFORMS</strong> to record a video testimonial straight from your phone.</p>\n<p>Remember, don&#8217;t worry about making it professional. We just want to hear your story, what you like about WPForms, and how has WPForms helped you grow your business.</p>\n<p>I look forward to watching your stories and better connecting with you.</p>\n<h3>What&#8217;s New in WPForms</h3>\n<p>We added a lot of powerful features over the last 12 months. Below are some of my favorite:</p>\n<p><strong><a href="https://wpforms.com/addons/conversational-forms-addon/" title="Conversational Forms by WPForms">Conversational Forms</a></strong></p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/interactive-conversational-forms-example.gif" alt="interactive conversational forms example" width="1030" height="742" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-391720" /></p>\n<p>Conversational Forms is the first true interactive form layout built exclusively for WordPress that is guaranteed to boost form completion and your overall form conversions (<a href="https://wpforms.com/conversational-forms-demo/" title="Conversational Forms Demo" rel="noopener" target="_blank">See Demo</a>).</p>\n<p>Conversational Forms help make your WordPress forms feel more human. Instead of asking all twenty questions at once, Conversational Forms takes the one question at a time approach similar to a face-to-face conversation.</p>\n<p>The full-page conversational form layout makes your form less overwhelming and more personal, leading to a better form completion rate.</p>\n<p><strong><a href="https://wpforms.com/addons/form-pages-addon/" title="Form Landing Pages by WPForms">Form Landing Pages</a></strong></p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/wpformsformpagesaddon-1.png" alt="Form Pages by WPForms" width="620" height="300" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-366613" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/wpformsformpagesaddon-1.png 620w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/wpformsformpagesaddon-1-300x145.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px" /></p>\n<p>Form Pages addon for WPForms is the first &#8220;distraction free&#8221; form landing page solution for WordPress (<a href="https://wpforms.com/form-pages-demo/" title="Form Pages Demo" rel="noopener" target="_blank">see demo</a>).</p>\n<p>It allows you to quickly create a dedicated form landing page without hiring a developer or writing any code in literally less than 5 minutes.</p>\n<p>Our distraction-free layout is designed to help you improve your overall form conversions!</p>\n<p><strong><a href="https://wpforms.com/addons/form-locker-addon/" title="Form Permissions for WPForms">Form Locker for Permissions &#038; Access Control</a></strong></p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/form-locker-settings.png" alt="form locker settings" width="562" height="359" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-370824" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/form-locker-settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/form-locker-settings-300x192.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>WPForms Form Locker addon allows you to lock your WordPress forms with various permissions and access control rules, so you can control who can fill out forms on your website.</p>\n<p>This includes: password protected forms, restrict forms to members only, limit the number of total submissions, limit one entry per person, and close form submissions after specific date / time.</p>\n<p><strong><a href="https://wpforms.com/introducing-wpforms-1-5-0-dashboard-widget-dynamic-field-population-wpforms-challenge-and-more/" title="WPForms Challenge and Dashboard Widget">WPForms Challenge + Dashboard Widget</a></strong></p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/more-steps-in-wpforms-challenge.png" alt="more steps in wpforms challenge" width="562" height="411" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-328672" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/more-steps-in-wpforms-challenge.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/more-steps-in-wpforms-challenge-300x219.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>To stay true to our mission, make smart WordPress forms easy, we created an internal challenge called the &#8220;WPForms challenge&#8221; which basically said users should be able to create a simple form and start collecting entries in less than 5 minutes. </p>\n<p>Every time we added a new feature, it was my goal to stress-test the user workflow and make sure that we always stay true to our mission.</p>\n<p>We made this challenge public in form of a guided wizard inside WPForms to not only help new users experience the WPForms difference, but so that every user can give us feedback and hold us accountable.</p>\n<p>As part of this release, we also added a Dashboard widget to give you a quick overview of your form&#8217;s performance.</p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/wpforms-dashboard-widget-1.png" alt="WPForms Dashboard Widget" width="620" height="452" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-330711" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/wpforms-dashboard-widget-1.png 620w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/wpforms-dashboard-widget-1-300x219.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px" /></p>\n<p><strong><a href="https://wpforms.com/new-stripe-recurring-functionality-for-your-payment-forms/" title="Stripe Recurring Payments">Stripe Recurring Payments</a> + <a href="https://wpforms.com/announcing-wpforms-1-5-1-form-builder-education-translations-and-payment-checkboxes/" title="Payment Checkboxes">Payment Checkboxes</a></strong></p>\n<p>One of the most requested features last year was Stripe recurring payments, and of course we listened to our users. We updated our Stripe addon to offer recurring payments ability.</p>\n<p>In a later update, we also added another highly requested feature: Payment Checkboxes, so you can create <a href="https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-simple-order-form-in-wordpress/" title="How to Create a Simple Order Form in WordPress (Step by Step)">simple order forms</a> within just clicks.</p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/payment-checkboxes.gif" alt="payment checkboxes" width="586" height="282" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-367410" /></p>\n<p><strong><a href="https://wpforms.com/announcing-the-wpforms-gutenberg-block-conditional-form-confirmations-and-more/" title="Conditional Form Confirmations">Conditional Form Confirmations</a></strong></p>\n<p>One of the most loved features in WPForms is our smart conditional logic. We expanded this feature last year, so you can also use it with your form notification and form confirmations.</p>\n<p>This lets you decide which form confirmation message people after they submit the form based on what they filled out in the form. </p>\n<p>It also lets you create smart form notifications and route the message internally to the right person or team in your organization.</p>\n<p><strong><a href="https://wpforms.com/introducing-new-gdpr-enhancements-for-your-wordpress-forms/" title="GDPR for WPForms">GDPR Enhancements for WPForms</a></strong></p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/gdprenhancements.png" alt="GDPR Enhancements for WPForms" width="620" height="300" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-199071" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/gdprenhancements.png 620w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/gdprenhancements-300x145.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px" /></p>\n<p>Last year simply cannot be summarized without mentioning GDPR. To help users stay compliant, we added GDPR enhancement features in WPForms for both our Pro and Lite users.</p>\n<p>This included GDPR form field, the ability to disable user cookies, the ability to disable storing of IP addresses, and more.</p>\n<h3>What&#8217;s Coming Next</h3>\n<p>I am truly inspired and proud of what the WPForms team has accomplished in the last 12 months, but there is a lot more to come. Were working on several new features that youve been asking for. Heres a quick preview of whats coming next:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Improved Entry Export &#8211; this update will focus on many requested features related to exporting.</li>\n<li>New Language Translations &#8211; we&#8217;re planning to translate WPForms into Portuguese and French.</li>\n<li>AJAX Form Submit &#8211; this is another frequently requested feature. It will allow users to submit forms without reloading the page which will make it easy to embed your forms in apps like <a href="https://optinmonster.com/" title="OptinMonster" rel="noopener" target="_blank">OptinMonster</a> and others.</li>\n<li>WP Mail SMTP Pro &#8211; we acquired <a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/wp-mail-smtp/" title="WP Mail SMTP" rel="noopener nofollow" target="_blank">WP Mail SMTP plugin</a> to help fix the WordPress email deliverability issues. While the free version is great, we&#8217;re launching a Pro version to add more powerful features and offer proper SMTP setup service.</li>\n<li>and of course a whole lot more &#8230;</li>\n</ul>\n<p>We&#8217;re always listening to user feedback for new feature ideas and improvements. If you ever have an idea for a new addon or feature that you&#8217;d like to see, please <a href="https://wpforms.com/contact/" title="Send us your feature ideas for WPForms">get in touch</a>.</p>\n<p>Thank you for your continued support in making WPForms the <a href="https://wpforms.com/" title="WPForms is the best WordPress Contact Form Plugin">best WordPress contact form plugin</a>.</p>\n<p><em>Syed and the WPForms Team</em></p>\n<p>P.S. Don&#8217;t have a WPForms Pro license? <a href="https://wpforms.com/pricing/" title="Get Started with WPForms Pro">Click here to get started today</a>, and experience the WPForms difference.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com/wpforms-turns-3/">WPForms Turns 3 Years Old &#8211; Bonus Prizes + What&#8217;s New &#038; What&#8217;s Coming Next</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com">WPForms</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:41:"https://wpforms.com/wpforms-turns-3/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:1;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:42:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:66:"[Case Study] 6 Ways WPBeginner Uses WPForms to Grow Their Business";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:71:"https://wpforms.com/how-wpbeginner-uses-wpforms-to-grow-their-business/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:79:"https://wpforms.com/how-wpbeginner-uses-wpforms-to-grow-their-business/#respond";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Mon, 25 Mar 2019 15:01:17 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Marketing";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:29:"https://wpforms.com/?p=425055";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:591:"<p>Aside from making smart forms easy, one of the things that make WPForms the best drag &#038; drop WordPress form builder is our focus on empowering business owners to grow their business. Every feature that we build is results driven. In this case study, I will share how WPBeginner is using WPForms to grow their [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com/how-wpbeginner-uses-wpforms-to-grow-their-business/">[Case Study] 6 Ways WPBeginner Uses WPForms to Grow Their Business</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com">WPForms</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11:"Syed Balkhi";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:10933:"<p>Aside from making smart forms easy, one of the things that make WPForms the best drag &#038; drop WordPress form builder is our focus on empowering business owners to grow their business.</p>\n<p>Every feature that we build is results driven. In this case study, I will share how WPBeginner is using WPForms to grow their blog traffic and revenue.</p>\n<h3>Meet WPBeginner</h3>\n<p><a href="https://www.wpbeginner.com/" title="WPBeginner" rel="noopener" target="_blank">WPBeginner</a> is the largest free WordPress resource site for beginners. </p>\n<p><a href="https://www.wpbeginner.com/" title="WPBeginner" rel="noopener" target="_blank"><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpbeginner-screenshot.png" alt="WPBeginner Screenshot" width="620" height="450" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-425140" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpbeginner-screenshot.png 620w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpbeginner-screenshot-300x218.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px" /></a></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> I&#8217;m also the founder of WPBeginner, and I had our team build WPForms, so we can have more business focused form features that were lacking in other WordPress plugins.</p>\n<p>Here are 6 ways we&#8217;re using WPForms on WPBeginner to increase our blog traffic and revenue.</p>\n<h3>1. Contact Form</h3>\n<p>Every website needs a contact form. It allows your website visitors an easy way to get in touch with you. </p>\n<p>Since WPBeginner get millions of visitors every month, it&#8217;s important for us to have a contact form that&#8217;s not only reliable, but has a way to block spam.</p>\n<p>WPForms comes with three built-in spam protection solutions: invisible honeypot, Google reCAPTCHA, and <a href="https://wpforms.com/addons/custom-catpcha-addon/" title="Custom Questions CAPTCHA for WordPress">custom questions CAPTCHA</a>.</p>\n<p>WPBeginner website uses the combination of invisible honeypot and Google reCAPTCHA which blocks out all spam.</p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpbeginnercontactform.png" alt="WPBeginner Contact Form" width="620" height="599" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-425142" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpbeginnercontactform.png 620w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpbeginnercontactform-300x290.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px" /></p>\n<p><strong>Pro Tip:</strong> <a href="https://wpforms.com/docs/setup-captcha-wpforms/" title="How to Set Up reCAPTCHA in WPForms">Setup reCAPTCHA on your WordPress forms</a> to reduce spam form submissions.</p>\n<h3>2. Grow Email List</h3>\n<p>Every industry expert knows that more than 70% of people leaving your website will never return. </p>\n<p>At WPBeginner, it&#8217;s important for us to convert as many website visitors into email subscribers, so we can continue to grow our website traffic and revenue.</p>\n<p>WPForms comes with built-in email marketing integrations for <a title="Constant Contact" href="https://wpforms.com/refer/constant-contact/" rel="nofollow nooperner" target="_blank">Constant Contact</a>, <a title="MailChimp" href="https://wpforms.com/refer/mailchimp/" rel="nofollow nooperner" target="_blank">MailChimp</a>, <a title="Drip" href="https://wpforms.com/refer/drip/" rel="nofollow nooperner" target="_blank">Drip</a>, <a  title="GetResponse" href="https://wpforms.com/refer/getresponse-2/" rel="nofollow nooperner" target="_blank" >GetResponse</a>, Campaign Monitor, and over 1000+ others through <a href="https://wpforms.com/addons/zapier-addon/" title="Zapier Addon">Zapier</a>.</p>\n<p>WPBeginner website uses WPForms native email marketing integration combined with smart conditional logic to turn all of our contact forms into newsletter signup forms.</p>\n<p>In each form, we add a checkbox field that asks users if they want to receive weekly WordPress tutorials and updates from WPBeginner. </p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpbeginner-contact-form-optin.png" alt="WPBeginner Contact Form Optin" width="620" height="568" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-425172" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpbeginner-contact-form-optin.png 620w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpbeginner-contact-form-optin-300x275.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px" /></p>\n<p>We use the conditional logic feature of WPForms to automatically subscribe any user who checks the box to our weekly email newsletter.</p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpforms-conditional-newsletter-signup.png" alt="WPForms Conditional Newsletter Signup Form" width="620" height="390" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-425170" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpforms-conditional-newsletter-signup.png 620w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpforms-conditional-newsletter-signup-300x189.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px" /></p>\n<h3>3. Reduce Form Abandonment</h3>\n<p>Form abandonment is a real problem. </p>\n<p>WPBeginner uses the <a href="https://wpforms.com/addons/form-abandonment-addon/" title="Form Abandonment Addon for WPForms">form abandonment</a> feature of WPForms to capture partial form submissions on our important business inquiry forms. This helps the team close more partnership deals.</p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/WPForms-Form-Abandonment-addon-settings.png" alt="WPForms Form Abandonment addon settings" width="468" height="282" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-192194" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/WPForms-Form-Abandonment-addon-settings.png 468w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/WPForms-Form-Abandonment-addon-settings-300x181.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 468px) 100vw, 468px" /></p>\n<p>Although it&#8217;s not live yet, WPBeginner team is also planning to use WPForms&#8217; distraction-free <a href="https://wpforms.com/addons/form-pages-addon/" title="Form Landing Pages for WordPress by WPForms">form landing pages</a> to reduce form abandonment on some of their lead forms.</p>\n<h3>4. Reader Surveys</h3>\n<p>WPBeginner team regularly conducts reader surveys to gather feedback and make data-driven decisions to grow the website.</p>\n<p>They use WPForms&#8217; powerful <a href="https://wpforms.com/addons/surveys-and-polls-addon/" title="Surveys and Polls by WPForms">survey and polls addon</a> to create smart survey forms, so they can get real-time insights from WPForms interactive survey reports. </p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/Graph-option-in-WPForms-survey-report.gif" alt="Graph option in WPForms survey report" width="756" height="566" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-148990" /></p>\n<p>Since some of the surveys require more granular permissions &#038; access control, WPBeginner team uses the <a href="https://wpforms.com/addons/form-locker-addon/" title="Form Locker Addon">form locker addon</a> by WPForms to limit the number of total submissions, password-protect forms, and automatically closing submissions after specific date.</p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/form-locker-settings.png" alt="form locker settings" width="562" height="359" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-370824" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/form-locker-settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/form-locker-settings-300x192.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>In the future, they are planning to use WPForms brand new <a href="https://wpforms.com/addons/conversational-forms-addon/" title="Conversational Forms Addon">conversational forms addon</a> to improve form completion rate.</p>\n<p><a class="btn btn-block" style="background-color: #659a17 !important; color: #fff !important; padding: 20px 25px !important; text-align: center; text-decoration: none; border-radius: 4px !important; -moz-border-radius: 4px !important; -webkit-border-radius: 4px !important; line-height: 48px; font-weight: bold;" title="Click here to join our affiliate program" href="https://wpforms.com/conversational-forms-demo/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Click here to see Conversational Form Demo</a></p>\n<h3>5. Get New Blog Post Ideas</h3>\n<p>Aside from reader surveys, WPBeginner also has a <a href="https://www.wpbeginner.com/make-a-suggestion/" title="Make a Suggestion to WPBeginner" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Make a Suggestion page</a> where users can submit blog post ideas.</p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpbeginner-make-a-suggestion.png" alt="WPBeginner Make a Suggestion Form" width="620" height="504" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-425205" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpbeginner-make-a-suggestion.png 620w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpbeginner-make-a-suggestion-300x244.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px" /></p>\n<p>WPBeginner team uses the responses from this form to plan their blog calendar.</p>\n<p>If you&#8217;re a blogger or even a regular business, you should definitely consider creating a Make a Suggestion page. You will be surprised how many great ideas will come from it.</p>\n<h3>6. Collect Payments</h3>\n<p>WPForms allows you to create <a href="https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-simple-order-form-in-wordpress/" title="How to Create a Simple Order Form in WordPress (Step by Step)">simple order forms</a> to accept payments right on your WordPress site.</p>\n<p>WPBeginner team uses WPForms to create simple payment forms that makes it easy for users to purchase support services. </p>\n<p>Although this is not a big chunk of revenue for WPBeginner since they do their best to offer free support, on rare occasions they may ask for a payment to solve a more complicated WordPress problem for a reader.</p>\n<h3>Final Thoughts</h3>\n<p>WPForms plays a very important role in growing WPBeginner traffic and revenue. Even though WPBeginner team does not use all of WPForms powerful features, they&#8217;re using several important features to streamline their workflow and grow the overall business.</p>\n<p>How are you using WPForms on your website? Leave a comment and let us know.</p>\n<p>Want to see all the powerful features that are available at WPForms? <a href="https://wpforms.com/features/" title="WPForms Features">Click here to see all WPForms features</a>. </p>\n<p>Not using WPForms on your site yet? Click here to <a href="https://wpforms.com/pricing/" title="https://wpforms.com/pricing/">get started with WPForms Pro</a>. </p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com/how-wpbeginner-uses-wpforms-to-grow-their-business/">[Case Study] 6 Ways WPBeginner Uses WPForms to Grow Their Business</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com">WPForms</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:76:"https://wpforms.com/how-wpbeginner-uses-wpforms-to-grow-their-business/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:2;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:51:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:72:"How to Securely Send WordPress Emails Using Gmail SMTP with WP Mail SMTP";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:75:"https://wpforms.com/how-to-securely-send-wordpress-emails-using-gmail-smtp/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:84:"https://wpforms.com/how-to-securely-send-wordpress-emails-using-gmail-smtp/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Fri, 22 Mar 2019 17:35:31 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:4:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:19:"WordPress Tutorials";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4:"smtp";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:17:"form notification";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:13:"notifications";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:28:"https://wpforms.com/?p=35577";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:611:"<p>Looking for a secure SMTP plugin that helps you receive email notifications from your WordPress contact forms? With WP Mail SMTP, you can fix delivery issues by authenticating emails through your Gmail or G Suite account &#8212; all while keeping your login credentials safe. In this post, well show you how to set up WP [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com/how-to-securely-send-wordpress-emails-using-gmail-smtp/">How to Securely Send WordPress Emails Using Gmail SMTP with WP Mail SMTP</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com">WPForms</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:13:"Shahzad Saeed";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:25533:"<p>Looking for a secure SMTP plugin that helps you receive email notifications from your WordPress contact forms? With WP Mail SMTP, you can fix delivery issues by authenticating emails through your Gmail or G Suite account &#8212; all while keeping your login credentials safe. </p>\n<p>In this post, well show you how to set up WP Mail SMTP for sending WordPress emails with your Gmail or G Suite email address.</p>\n<h3>Why Youre Not Receiving Notifications</h3>\n<p>By default, WordPress uses the <a href="http://www.wpbeginner.com/glossary/php/" target="_blank">PHP</a> mail function to send emails generated by WordPress or any contact plugin like<a href="http://wpforms.com/">WPForms</a>. The most common reason for not getting emails is that yourWordPress hostingserver is not configured to use PHP mail function.</p>\n<p>In addition to this, anti-spam efforts by email providers can impact your emails as well. As part of their filtering process, many email providers will check whether your email originates from the same domain noted in the From Email. For example, if your email claims to be sent from your Gmail address but is actually sent from your website&#8217;s server (rather than Gmail&#8217;s server), your email may be sent to spam or not be delivered at all.</p>\n<p>You can fix this by using SMTP instead of the PHP mail function.SMTP (Simple Mail Transfer Protocol) is the industry standard for sending emails reliably.</p>\n<h3>Why Use the WP Mail SMTP Plugin?</h3>\n<p>The main benefit of using the WP Mail SMTP plugin is that it lets you send WordPress emails securely using your Gmail or G Suite account without requiring to enable less secure apps in your account.</p>\n<p>In addition, unlike many other SMTP options, you wont need to enter your Gmail username and password in your WordPress dashboard where other site users can see them. By using this method, you&#8217;ll help to <a href="http://www.wpbeginner.com/wordpress-security/" target="_blank" title="Ultimate Guide to WordPress Security">keep your WordPress site secure</a>.</p>\n<p>Lets take a look at how to set up WP Mail SMTP for sending WordPress emails.</p>\n<h3>Step 1: Install the WP Mail SMTP Plugin</h3>\n<p>The first thing you need to do is to install and activate the<a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/wp-mail-smtp/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">WP Mail SMTP</a>plugin. For step-by-step instructions, you can check out <a href="http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/step-by-step-guide-to-install-a-wordpress-plugin-for-beginners/" target="_blank">WPBeginner&#8217;s guide on how to install a WordPress plugin</a>.</p>\n<p>After installing and activating WP Mail SMTP, go to<strong>Settings  WP MailSMTP</strong> to open the plugin settings page. </p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Open-WP-Mail-SMTP-settings-page-1.png" alt="Open WP Mail SMTP settings page" width="450" height="309" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-423553" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Open-WP-Mail-SMTP-settings-page-1.png 450w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Open-WP-Mail-SMTP-settings-page-1-300x206.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 450px) 100vw, 450px" /></p>\n<p>At the top of this page, you&#8217;ll see the <strong>From Email</strong> and <strong>From Name</strong>. You can ignore these settings, because Google will automatically force these values to match the email account used in the next step.</p>\n<p>To start the setup process, you&#8217;ll need to scroll to the <strong>Mailer</strong> field and select the <strong>Google</strong> option.</p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Select-Google-mailer-option-in-WP-Mail-SMTP-1.png" alt="Select Google mailer option in WP Mail SMTP" width="562" height="214" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-423571" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Select-Google-mailer-option-in-WP-Mail-SMTP-1.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Select-Google-mailer-option-in-WP-Mail-SMTP-1-300x114.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<div class="alert alert-warning"><strong>Note:</strong> Google&#8217;s API (used by the Google mailer) will not allow you to customize certain aspects of your emails, such as the Reply To email address. If this is an important option in your project, please consider using <a href="https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-fix-wordpress-contact-form-not-sending-email-with-smtp/" title="How to Fix WordPress Contact Form Not Sending Email With SMTP">an alternative mailer option</a>.</div>\n<p>You can skip the <strong>Return Path</strong> checkbox, as Google does not allow this setting to be altered.</p>\n<p>Next, you should see a new Gmail section appear. Here, you&#8217;ll see fields for <strong>Client Secret</strong> and <strong>Client ID</strong>.</p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Gmail-section-of-WP-Mail-SMTP-settings.png" alt="Gmail section of WP Mail SMTP settings" width="562" height="359" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-423589" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Gmail-section-of-WP-Mail-SMTP-settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Gmail-section-of-WP-Mail-SMTP-settings-300x192.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>To get the information for these fields, you&#8217;ll need to create a web application through your Google account. This doesn&#8217;t require any coding, and we&#8217;ll show you exactly what to do.</p>\n<h3>Step 2: Create a Web Application</h3>\n<p>To create an application, you&#8217;ll first need to <a href="https://console.developers.google.com/flows/enableapi?apiid=gmail&#038;pli=1" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">sign into your Gmail account and access Gmail&#8217;s application registration</a>. Clicking that link should open this Google page in a new tab or window, and you&#8217;ll want to keep your site settings open (we&#8217;ll return to those later).</p>\n<p>Once you&#8217;ve followed that link and logged into your Gmail account, you should see a form named &#8220;Register your application for Gmail API in Google API Console&#8221;. </p>\n<p>In the dropdown labeled <strong>Select a project where your application will be registered</strong>, leave the default option of <strong>Create a project</strong>. In some cases, you may also be asked to agree to terms of service.</p>\n<p>After filling out this form, go ahead and click the <strong>Continue</strong> button.</p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Create-a-new-project-for-Google-application.jpg" alt="Create a new project for Google application" width="562" height="323" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-423633" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Create-a-new-project-for-Google-application.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Create-a-new-project-for-Google-application-300x172.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>Next, you should see a screen that says &#8220;The API is enabled&#8221;. To proceed to the setup page, click the <strong>Go to credentials</strong> button.</p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Gmail-API-is-enabled.png" alt="Gmail API is enabled" width="500" height="205" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-423593" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Gmail-API-is-enabled.png 500w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Gmail-API-is-enabled-300x123.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px" /></p>\n<p>In the next page, youll be prompted to determine the credentials you need. Here are the fields on this page and the options you&#8217;ll need to select:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Which API are you using?</strong> Gmail API</li>\n<li><strong>Where will you be calling the API from?</strong> Web server (e.g. node.js, Tomcat)</li>\n<li><strong>What data will you be accessing?</strong> User data</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Once you&#8217;ve made these selections, click the <strong>What credentials do I need?</strong> button to go to the next step.</p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Add-credentials-to-Gmail-app-project.png" alt="Add credentials to Gmail app project" width="500" height="513" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-423600" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Add-credentials-to-Gmail-app-project.png 500w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Add-credentials-to-Gmail-app-project-292x300.png 292w" sizes="(max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px" /></p>\n<p>After clicking this button, Google will show a popup asking you to set up a consent screen. Go ahead and click on the <strong>Set Up Consent Screen Option</strong>. </p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Open-OAuth-consent-screen.png" alt="Open OAuth consent screen" width="562" height="279" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-422938" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Open-OAuth-consent-screen.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Open-OAuth-consent-screen-300x149.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>This will open a new tab or window. Be sure to keep the original tab/window open, as we&#8217;ll return to it a little later.</p>\n<p>In the new tab/window, you&#8217;ll be asked for several details to prepare your consent screen. This is the permissions screen that will display to you later in the setup process (never seen by your users).</p>\n<p>If you have a G Suite account, you&#8217;ll first set <strong>Application type</strong> to <strong>Internal</strong>. You will not see this option if you&#8217;re using an @gmail.com email account.</p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Select-internal-application-type.jpg" alt="Select internal application type" width="562" height="381" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-423628" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Select-internal-application-type.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Select-internal-application-type-300x203.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>For <strong>Application name,</strong> you can add the name of your website (or any other name that feels logical to you).</p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Fill-in-app-details.png" alt="Fill in app details" width="562" height="365" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-422941" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Fill-in-app-details.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Fill-in-app-details-300x195.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>Then, you can skip down to <strong>Authorized domains</strong> and add the URL for your website. Be sure to not include <code>http://</code> or <code>https://</code> here.</p>\n<p>For <strong>Application Homepage link</strong>, <strong>Application Privacy Policy link</strong>, and <strong>Application Terms of Service link</strong>, you can again just add your website URL. You don&#8217;t need to have special privacy or terms pages in place for this app, as again this consent screen will only ever be seen by you.</p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Add-authorized-domain-information-to-Google-consent.png" alt="Add authorized domain information to Google consent" width="588" height="562" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-423477" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Add-authorized-domain-information-to-Google-consent.png 588w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Add-authorized-domain-information-to-Google-consent-300x287.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 588px) 100vw, 588px" /></p>\n<p>When you&#8217;re ready, click the <strong>Save</strong> button at the bottom of this screen.</p>\n<p>After saving your consent screen settings, Google will take you back to an API credentials screen. You can ignore this, and instead return to the first tab/window. </p>\n<p>For this step, you&#8217;ll be creating an OAuth client ID. OAuth, or Open Authorization, is what will provide permission for your website to use your Gmail account to authenticate emails.</p>\n<p>For the <strong>Name</strong> field, enter anything you like or leave the default name. This is only for reference within your Google account.</p>\n<p>For <strong>Authorized JavaScript origins</strong>, you&#8217;ll need to enter your site&#8217;s URL.</p>\n<p>Last, we need to fill out the <strong>Authorized redirect URIs</strong> field. To get the URI for your site, you&#8217;ll need to go back to the tab or window with your WordPress site. Still on the <strong>Settings &raquo; WP Mail SMTP</strong> page, you&#8217;ll need to look under the Gmail section for the field labeled <strong>Authorized redirect URI</strong>.</p>\n<p>The value in this field should be your site&#8217;s URL followed by some extra details. You&#8217;ll need to copy this value, which is easily done by clicking the button with the copy icon. </p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Use-button-to-copy-authorized-redirect-URI-from-WP-Mail-SMTP-settings.png" alt="Use button to copy authorized redirect URI from WP Mail SMTP settings" width="562" height="134" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-423641" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Use-button-to-copy-authorized-redirect-URI-from-WP-Mail-SMTP-settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Use-button-to-copy-authorized-redirect-URI-from-WP-Mail-SMTP-settings-300x72.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>After copying the URI, return to the Google APIs page and paste it into the field under <strong>Authorized redirect URIs</strong>.</p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Create-OAuth-client-ID.png" alt="Create OAuth client ID" width="562" height="633" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-423481" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Create-OAuth-client-ID.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Create-OAuth-client-ID-266x300.png 266w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>When you finish filling out these details, you may see a <strong>Refresh</strong> button near the bottom of the page. Go ahead and click this.</p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Click-Refresh-button.png" alt="Click Refresh button" width="437" height="267" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-423519" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Click-Refresh-button.png 437w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Click-Refresh-button-300x183.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 437px) 100vw, 437px" /></p>\n<p>Next, you can click the <strong>Create client ID</strong> button.</p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Click-blue-button-to-create-OAuth-client-ID.png" alt="Click blue button to create OAuth client ID" width="386" height="264" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-423522" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Click-blue-button-to-create-OAuth-client-ID.png 386w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Click-blue-button-to-create-OAuth-client-ID-300x205.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 386px) 100vw, 386px" /></p>\n<p>Youve now successfully created a Google web application!</p>\n<p>Now we need to see the full details. On the last screen, click <strong>Ill do this later</strong> to go to the Credentials page.</p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Click-Ill-do-this-later.png" alt="Click Ill do this later" width="462" height="496" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-423524" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Click-Ill-do-this-later.png 462w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Click-Ill-do-this-later-279x300.png 279w" sizes="(max-width: 462px) 100vw, 462px" /></p>\n<h3 id="step-3">Step 3: Grant Permissions and Send Test Email</h3>\n<p>On the Credentials page, you can now see the details of the web application you just created. To view <strong>Client ID</strong> and <strong>Client Secret</strong>, click the pencil icon.</p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Click-pencil-icon-to-see-details.png" alt="Click pencil icon to see details" width="562" height="100" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-423506" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Click-pencil-icon-to-see-details.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Click-pencil-icon-to-see-details-300x53.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>This will open all of the details for your app. On this page, you&#8217;ll see the <strong>Client ID</strong> and <strong>Client secret</strong> values.</p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Copy-Client-ID-and-Client-secret.png" alt="Copy Client ID and Client secret" width="562" height="299" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-423510" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Copy-Client-ID-and-Client-secret.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Copy-Client-ID-and-Client-secret-300x160.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>Each of these will need to be copied into your WP Mail SMTP settings back in your WordPress admin screen.</p>\n<div class="alert alert-warning"><strong>Note:</strong> Be very careful not to copy any extra text or spaces with your Client ID or Client Secret, as this will result in an error in the next step.</div>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Copy-in-Client-ID-and-secret-to-WP-Mail-SMTP-settings.png" alt="Copy in Client ID and secret to WP Mail SMTP settings" width="620" height="243" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-118086" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Copy-in-Client-ID-and-secret-to-WP-Mail-SMTP-settings.png 620w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Copy-in-Client-ID-and-secret-to-WP-Mail-SMTP-settings-300x118.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px" /></p>\n<p>After saving these settings, the page will refresh. Before Google allows this information to be used to connect to your account, however, you must grant permission. </p>\n<p>To do this, scroll to the bottom of this page and click the button labeled <strong>Allow plugin to send emails using your Google account</strong>.</p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Authorize-plugin-to-send-emails-with-Gmail.png" alt="Authorize plugin to send emails with Gmail" width="562" height="178" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-423617" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Authorize-plugin-to-send-emails-with-Gmail.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Authorize-plugin-to-send-emails-with-Gmail-300x95.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>This will open a login screen for Google. Go ahead and log into the account you&#8217;re setting this SMTP up with. Then, you&#8217;ll see a screen asking for permission for this site to send email on your behalf. </p>\n<p>When you&#8217;re ready, click the <strong>Allow</strong> button to proceed.</p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Provide-permissions-to-your-Google-app.png" alt="Provide permissions to your Google app" width="462" height="574" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-423529" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Provide-permissions-to-your-Google-app.png 462w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Provide-permissions-to-your-Google-app-241x300.png 241w" sizes="(max-width: 462px) 100vw, 462px" /></p>\n<p>Next, you&#8217;ll be returned to your WP Mail SMTP settings and a success message will be displayed. Now that the connection is complete, you&#8217;re ready to send a test email under the <strong>Email Test</strong> tab.</p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Gmail-connection-success-with-WP-Mail-SMTP.png" alt="Gmail connection success with WP Mail SMTP" width="562" height="290" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-423625" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Gmail-connection-success-with-WP-Mail-SMTP.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Gmail-connection-success-with-WP-Mail-SMTP-300x155.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>Once the Test Email tab is open, you&#8217;ll need to enter a valid email address and click the <strong>Send Email</strong> button. Be sure to use an email address you have access to so you can confirm the email is delivered.</p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Send-a-test-email-through-WP-Mail-SMTP.png" alt="Send a test email through WP Mail SMTP" width="430" height="360" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-118145" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Send-a-test-email-through-WP-Mail-SMTP.png 430w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Send-a-test-email-through-WP-Mail-SMTP-300x251.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 430px) 100vw, 430px" /></p>\n<p>When the test message has been sent, you&#8217;ll see a success message at the top of this tab.</p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/WP-Mail-SMTP-test-email-was-sent-successfully.png" alt="WP Mail SMTP test email was sent successfully" width="292" height="274" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-118113" /></p>\n<p>You should also soon receive a test email at the email address you entered.</p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Test-email-for-WP-Mail-SMTP-Gmail.png" alt="Test email for WP Mail SMTP Gmail" width="562" height="431" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-423663" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Test-email-for-WP-Mail-SMTP-Gmail.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Test-email-for-WP-Mail-SMTP-Gmail-300x230.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<h3>Frequently Asked Questions</h3>\n<h6>What If the Test Email Doesn&#8217;t Send Successfully?</h6>\n<p>If the SMTP test email isn&#8217;t able to send, a debug log will appear with additional details. Here are some of the possible error messages and how to resolve them.</p>\n<p><strong>401. Thats an error.<br />\nError: invalid_client</strong><br />\nThis error appears when the Client ID isn&#8217;t able to be read properly. To fix, try copying the Client ID in again and check that there&#8217;s no whitespace or extra text.</p>\n<p><strong>400. Thats an error.<br />\nError: invalid_request<br />\nMissing required parameter: client_id</strong><br />\nThis error will display when the Client ID field is empty or not able to be read properly. To fix, copy in the Client ID again and be careful to not add extra text or whitespace.</p>\n<p><strong>cURL error 60: SSL certificate problem</strong><br />\nThis message means that the server is missing a certificate thats required for SMTP to work. To fix, you&#8217;ll need to contact your site&#8217;s hosting provider to ask them to install this certificate (most likely the cacert.pem certificate, though it&#8217;s best to ask your host to check).</p>\n<p><strong>code: 401,<br />\nmessage: Login Required</strong><br />\nIf you see this in the debug message, permission still needs to be granted to your use Google account. For instructions on how to fix this, please see <a href="#step-3" title="Step 3: Grant Permissions and Send Test Email">Step 3</a> of this tutorial. Also, be sure to check that the From Email in your SMTP settings matches the email used to setup the Google app.</p>\n<h6>What If I Want to Switch to A Different Email Later?</h6>\n<p>If you&#8217;d like to change to a different Gmail/G Suite email address, you&#8217;ll need to repeat all tutorial steps above. This includes generating a new Client ID and Client Secret under this other email account.</p>\n<p>When you get to the Authorization step (under Step 3), save your settings and then click the <strong>Remove Connection</strong> button. This will remove the authorization for your original email account and allow you to repeat the authorization steps with the new email.</p>\n<p><img src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Remove-connection-in-WP-Mail-SMTP.png" alt="Remove connection in WP Mail SMTP" width="703" height="124" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-223847" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Remove-connection-in-WP-Mail-SMTP.png 703w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Remove-connection-in-WP-Mail-SMTP-300x53.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 703px) 100vw, 703px" /></p>\n<p>Thats it! Youve successfully configuredWP Mail SMTP&#8217;s Google mailer on your WordPress site.</p>\n<p>What are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful<a href="https://wpforms.com/">WordPress forms plugin</a>today.</p>\n<p>If you like this article, then please follow us on<a href="http://facebook.com/wpforms" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Facebook</a>and<a href="http://twitter.com/easywpforms" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Twitter</a>for more free WordPress tutorials.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com/how-to-securely-send-wordpress-emails-using-gmail-smtp/">How to Securely Send WordPress Emails Using Gmail SMTP with WP Mail SMTP</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com">WPForms</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:80:"https://wpforms.com/how-to-securely-send-wordpress-emails-using-gmail-smtp/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3:"810";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:3;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:54:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:62:"How to Create a Video Release Form in WordPress (Step by Step)";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:81:"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-video-release-form-in-wordpress-step-by-step/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:89:"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-video-release-form-in-wordpress-step-by-step/#respond";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Tue, 05 Mar 2019 13:00:51 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:5:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:19:"WordPress Tutorials";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:7:"WPForms";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:15:"signature addon";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:18:"video release form";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:15:"video marketing";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:29:"https://wpforms.com/?p=390974";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:593:"<p>Do you need an easy and efficient way to get peoples consent to use video footage that youve taken of them during activities and at events? Its crucial you have peoples permission to take and use video of them. In this article, well show you how to create a video release form in WordPress. The [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-video-release-form-in-wordpress-step-by-step/">How to Create a Video Release Form in WordPress (Step by Step)</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com">WPForms</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:14:"Lindsay Liedke";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:15135:"<p>Do you need an easy and efficient way to get peoples consent to use video footage that youve taken of them during activities and at events? Its crucial you have peoples permission to take and use video of them.</p>\n<p>In this article, well show you how to create a video release form in WordPress.</p>\n<h3>The Importance of a Video Release Form</h3>\n<p>If youre a video producer its in your best interest to always have anyone recorded fill out a video production release form so you avoid any liability and have the opportunity to do what you want with the footage.</p>\n<p>Here are some reasons why video release forms are so important:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Anyone that doesnt fill out a video release form may later ask you to pull their likeness from your video</li>\n<li>If you videotape a minor and dont have parental consent, you could face legal trouble</li>\n<li>So the signer of the video release form can release their right to approve or disapprove of the finished product</li>\n<li>To give people the impression you are a professional and care about their rights</li>\n<li>To ensure those in your film are not violating another contract theyve signed, and removing liability from yourself if they are</li>\n<li>Because its the nice thing to do, even if youre in a public place and dont technically need permission</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If you approach people in a nice, professional way when videotaping at an event or activity, chances are theyll sign the form without a problem. And if they dont, and give you a hassle, just be happy you avoided having to deal with them later after youve edited your film and they want out of it.</p>\n<p>Lets take a look at how to create a video release form in WordPress.</p>\n<h3>Step 1: Create a Video Release Form in WordPress</h3>\n<p>Using WPForms is the easiest way to create a standard video release form in WordPress. WPForms comes with the <a href="https://wpforms.com/addons/form-templates-pack-addon/">Form Templates Pack addon</a> that allows you to choose from 100+ pre-built templates for every niche and industry, including a video release form template.</p>\n<p>The first thing youll need to do is install and activate the <a href="https://wpforms.com/pricing/">WPForms plugin</a>. For more details, see this step by step guide on <a title="Step by step guide on How to Install a WordPress Plugin" href="http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/step-by-step-guide-to-install-a-wordpress-plugin-for-beginners/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">how to install a plugin in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>Next, youll need to install and activate the Form Templates Pack addon.</p>\n<p>To do this, go to <strong>WPForms</strong>  <strong>Addon</strong> and find the one labeled <strong>Form Templates Pack addon</strong>.</p>\n<p>Click <strong>Install Addon</strong> and then <strong>Activate</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-291194" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-templates-pack-addon.png" alt="form templates pack addon" width="562" height="193" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-templates-pack-addon.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-templates-pack-addon-300x103.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>Now youll need to create a new form.</p>\n<p>To do this, go to <strong>WPForms</strong>  <strong>Add New</strong>, and name your form. Then, scroll down to the section labeled <strong>Additional Templates</strong> and type video release into the search bar.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-390996" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/video-release-form-template.png" alt="" width="562" height="255" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/video-release-form-template.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/video-release-form-template-300x136.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>When the pre-built video release form template loads, most of the work is already done for you.</p>\n<p>Youll see form fields for the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Name of person in the video</li>\n<li>Section Divider with terms and conditions</li>\n<li>Date / Time</li>\n<li>Agreement checkbox</li>\n</ul>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-390994" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/video-release-form.png" alt="video release form" width="562" height="425" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/video-release-form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/video-release-form-300x227.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>If you want to see the online video release form template in action, head over and check out our <a href="https://wpforms.com/demo/video-release-form-demo/">sample video release form demo</a>.</p>\n<p>You can add additional fields to your form by dragging them from the left hand panel to the right hand panel.</p>\n<p>Then, click on the field to make any changes. You can also click on a form field and drag it to rearrange the order on your Video release form.</p>\n<p>For example, if you want to require a parent or guardian signature on your forms because its a video release form for minors, add the <strong>Signature</strong> form field to your video release form template.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-390993" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/signature-form-field-example.png" alt="signature form field example" width="562" height="372" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/signature-form-field-example.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/signature-form-field-example-300x199.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>Just make sure to select the <strong>Required</strong> checkbox so parents or guardians cant submit their form without a signature.</p>\n<p>You might also consider adding Name, Email, or Phone form fields to your video release form template so you can get in touch with people youve recorded later for any reason.</p>\n<p>When your video release form looks the way you want it to, click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Step 2: Configure Your Video Release Form Settings</h3>\n<p>To start, go to <strong>Settings</strong>  <strong>General</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-246850" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-General-Settings.png" alt="WPForms General Settings" width="562" height="443" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-General-Settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-General-Settings-300x236.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>Here you can configure the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Form Name.</strong> Rename your form here.</li>\n<li><strong>Form Description.</strong> Give your form a description.</li>\n<li><strong>Submit Button Text.</strong> Customize the copy on the submit button.</li>\n<li><strong>Spam Prevention.</strong> <a href="https://wpforms.com/how-to-build-a-spam-free-contact-form-without-captcha/">Enable the anti-spam honeypot feature</a> to prevent spam race submissions and <a href="https://www.wpbeginner.com/wordpress-security/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">keep your website secure</a>. This feature is automatically enabled on all WordPress forms. If you decide to use another form of spam prevention, you can either unclick this option or continue using this feature with other spam prevention features such as recaptcha.</li>\n<li><strong>GDPR Enhancements.</strong> You can disable the storing of entry information and user details, such as IP addresses and user agents, in an effort to <a href="https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-create-gdpr-compliant-forms/">comply with GDPR requirements</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Step 3: Configure Your Video Release Form Notifications</h3>\n<p>Notifications are a great way to send an email whenever someone submits a video release form on your website.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-246852" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-Notifications-Settings.png" alt="WPForms Notifications Settings" width="562" height="228" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-Notifications-Settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-Notifications-Settings-300x122.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>In fact, unless you disable this feature, whenever someone submits a video release form on your site, youll get a notification about it.</p>\n<p>If you <a href="https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-use-smart-tags-in-wpforms/">use smart tags</a>, you can also send a notification to people who fill out a video release form, letting them know youve received their form and will be in contact shortly if need be. This assures people their release form has gone through properly.</p>\n<p>You can also add important information to the notification about their video release form and the footage that was taken of them. For instance, you can mention where they might be able to view their footage when it airs. You can also include information about when and where the footage was taken so theres no confusion later on.</p>\n<p>For help with this step, check out our documentation on <a href="https://wpforms.com/docs/setup-form-notification-wpforms/">how to set up form notifications in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>You can send more than one notification when someone submits a video release form on your site. For example, you can send a notification to yourself, those that were recorded, and anyone on your production team that might need access to the release, and later the actual footage.</p>\n<p>For help doing this, check out our step by step tutorial on <a href="https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-multiple-form-notifications-in-wordpress-forms/">how to send multiple form notifications in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>Lastly, if you want to keep branding across your emails consistent, you can check out this guide on <a href="https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-add-custom-header-image-in-your-wpforms-email-template/">adding a custom header to your email template</a>.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-211599" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header.jpg" alt="Custom Email Header" width="562" height="314" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header-300x168.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>This will give your video release form a professional touch and make people filling it out feel more at ease when releasing their rights to the video footage.</p>\n<h3>Step 4: Configure Your Video Release Form Confirmations</h3>\n<p>Form confirmations are messages that display to people once they submit a video release form on your website. They let people know that their form has gone through and offer you the chance to let them know what the next steps are.</p>\n<p>WPForms has three confirmation types:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Message.</strong> This is the default confirmation type in WPForms. When someone submits a video release form, a simple message confirmation will appear letting them know their form was received and is being processed.</li>\n<li><strong>Show Page.</strong> This confirmation type will take customers to a specific web page on your site thanking them. For help doing this, check out our tutorial on <a href="https://wpforms.com/how-to-redirect-users-after-wordpress-form-submit/">redirecting customers to a thank you page</a>.</li>\n<li><strong>Go to URL (Redirect).</strong> This option is used when you want to send people to a different website.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Lets see <a href="https://wpforms.com/docs/setup-form-confirmation-wpforms/">how to set up a simple form confirmation in WPForms</a> so you can customize the message people will see when they fill out a video release form on your website.</p>\n<p>To start, click on the <strong>Confirmation</strong> tab in the Form Editor under <strong>Settings</strong>.</p>\n<p>Next, select the type of confirmation type youd like to create. For this example, well select <strong>Message</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-246854" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Confirmation-Message.png" alt="Confirmation Message" width="562" height="290" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Confirmation-Message.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Confirmation-Message-300x155.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>Then, customize the confirmation message to your liking and click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Step 7: Add Your Video Release Form to Your Website</h3>\n<p>After youve created a video release form, you need to add it to your WordPress website.</p>\n<p>WPForms allows you to add your forms to many locations on your website, including your blog posts, pages, and even <a href="https://wpforms.com/how-to-add-a-contact-form-in-wordpress-sidebar-widget/">sidebar widgets</a>.</p>\n<p>Lets take a look at the most common post/page embed option.</p>\n<p>To start, create a new post or page in WordPress and then click on the <strong>Add Form</strong> button.</p>\n<p>Next, select your video release form in the modal popup and click <strong>Add Form</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-390991" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/add-video-release-form.png" alt="add video release form" width="562" height="354" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/add-video-release-form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/add-video-release-form-300x189.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>Then, publish your post or page so your form will appear on your website.</p>\n<p>And there you have it! You now know how to create a video release form in WordPress.</p>\n<p>If you&#8217;re interested in using the video footage you&#8217;ve captured for promoting your business, be sure to check out this <a href="https://wpforms.com/the-ultimate-list-of-online-business-statistics/#video-marketing">roundup of online business stats</a> and focus on the video marketing section.</p>\n<p>So, what are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful <a href="https://wpforms.com">WordPress forms plugin</a> today.</p>\n<p>And dont forget, if you like this article, then please follow us on <a href="https://www.facebook.com/wpforms" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">Facebook</a> and <a href="http://twitter.com/easywpforms" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">Twitter</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-video-release-form-in-wordpress-step-by-step/">How to Create a Video Release Form in WordPress (Step by Step)</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com">WPForms</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:86:"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-video-release-form-in-wordpress-step-by-step/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:4;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:54:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:48:"How to Create a Simple Contact Form in WordPress";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:69:"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-simple-contact-form-in-wordpress/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:78:"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-simple-contact-form-in-wordpress/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Thu, 28 Feb 2019 13:00:51 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:5:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:19:"WordPress Tutorials";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:14:"wordpress form";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:12:"contact form";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:17:"form notification";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:15:"GDPR Form Field";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:27:"https://wpforms.com/?p=1188";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:539:"<p>Do you want to add a contact form to your WordPress website? As a site owner, you need to give your readers an easy way to get in touch with you. In this article, well show you how to create a simple contact form in WordPress. Why Create a Simple Contact Form in WordPress? When [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-simple-contact-form-in-wordpress/">How to Create a Simple Contact Form in WordPress</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com">WPForms</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:14:"Lindsay Liedke";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:23449:"<p>Do you want to add a contact form to your WordPress website? As a site owner, you need to give your readers an easy way to get in touch with you.</p>\n<p>In this article, well show you how to create a simple contact form in WordPress.</p>\n<h3>Why Create a Simple Contact Form in WordPress?</h3>\n<p>When you&#8217;re a new website owner, you may wonder <a href="https://wpforms.com/contact-form-vs-email-address-which-is-better/">whether to use a contact form or provide an email address</a> on your website.</p>\n<p>To help answer that question, here are the benefits of adding a contact form to your website:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Communication. </strong>Contact forms are a great way to allow your readers to quickly communicate with you.</li>\n<li><strong>Security. </strong>You keep your email safe from spammers. Since your contact form doesnt show your email address, spammers cant steal it.</li>\n<li><strong>Organization. </strong>With a contact form you can create <a href="https://optinmonster.com/101-email-subject-lines-your-subscribers-cant-resist/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">specific subject lines</a>, so people always know their emails are coming from you, and more importantly what the email is about.</li>\n<li><strong>Information. </strong>You control the information collected by adding only the fields you want site visitors to fill out on the form. This cuts down on the back and forth emails between you and a potential client.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Now let&#8217;s take a look at how to create a simple contact form in WordPress both by taking the WPForms Challenge and the traditional way youll create forms after knowing how to use WPForms.</p>\n<p>Here are some quick links to make things easier on you:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="#wpforms-challenge">Take the WPForms Challenge</a></li>\n<li><a href="#create-contact-form">Create a Simple Contact Form</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id="wpforms-challenge">Take the WPForms Challenge  Create a Form in Under 5 Minutes</h3>\n<p>We created WPForms with the intention of it being the easiest, most beginner friendly form builder plugin in the market. And to prove that to you, we created the WPForms Challenge. We challenge all new users of WPForms to create their first form <strong>in under 5 minutes</strong> to show them just how simple this contact form solution is.</p>\n<p>The first thing youll need to do is install and activate the <a href="https://wpforms.com/pricing/">WPForms plugin</a>. For more details, see this step by step guide on <a title="Step by step guide on How to Install a WordPress Plugin" href="http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/step-by-step-guide-to-install-a-wordpress-plugin-for-beginners/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">how to install a plugin in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>Once activated, youll be prompted with WPForms setup wizard and the option to take the WPForms Challenge.</p>\n<p>Click <strong>Start the WPForms Challenge</strong> to get started.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-397505" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/start-the-wpforms-challenge.png" alt="start the wpforms challenge" width="562" height="250" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/start-the-wpforms-challenge.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/start-the-wpforms-challenge-300x133.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p><strong>Step 1: Create Your First Form</strong></p>\n<p>Youll be taken immediately to the WPForms form builder when you start the WPForms Challenge. This is where youll create your first form and configure all of its settings.</p>\n<p>Youll see in the bottom right hand corner that there is a convenient checklist that will follow you as you create your form so you know you havent missed any steps. It also has a timer to show you how long you&#8217;ve spent creating your form.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-397499" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/challenge-checklist-and-timer.png" alt="challenge checklist and timer" width="562" height="347" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/challenge-checklist-and-timer.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/challenge-checklist-and-timer-300x185.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>The first step in the challenge is to name your form. For our example, well name our form Simple Contact Form.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-397502" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/name-your-form.png" alt="name your form" width="562" height="173" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/name-your-form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/name-your-form-300x92.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>Click <strong>Done</strong> to move to the next step. You&#8217;ll see in the next step that the checklist has crossed out the Name Your Form step. This shows you that youre on the right track.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 2: Customize Your Form Fields</strong></p>\n<p>Next its time to select a pre-designed template or use the blank template if you prefer to build your form from scratch. Since were creating a contact form, well select the <strong>Simple Contact Form</strong> template.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-397503" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/select-a-template.png" alt="select a template" width="562" height="459" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/select-a-template.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/select-a-template-300x245.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>When you click on the template you want to use, youll be taken to the part in the form builder that lets you add or remove form fields and customize the way they look and function. This part of form creation is optional.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-397498" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/add-form-fields-to-form.png" alt="add form fields to form" width="562" height="454" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/add-form-fields-to-form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/add-form-fields-to-form-300x242.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>We strive to make form building as simple and beginner friendly as possible. All of our templates have the basic form fields youll need without having to add or remove any fields.</p>\n<p>That said, we also strive to pack WPForms with powerful features so you can extend your form building capabilities and customize your forms to meet your needs.</p>\n<p>You can add additional fields to your contact form by dragging them from the left hand panel to the right hand panel.</p>\n<p>Then, click on the field to make any changes. You can also click on a form field and drag it to rearrange the order on your contact form.</p>\n<p>Once youre finished customizing your form, click <strong>Done</strong>.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 3: Check Notification Settings</strong></p>\n<p>The next step in the WPForms Challenge deals with your form&#8217;s notification settings.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-397501" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/form-notifications.png" alt="form notifications" width="562" height="362" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/form-notifications.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/form-notifications-300x193.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>Notifications are a great way to send an email whenever a contact form is submitted on your website. In fact, unless you disable this feature, whenever someone submits a contact form on your site, youll get a notification about it.</p>\n<p>If you <a href="https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-use-smart-tags-in-wpforms/">use smart tags</a>, you can also send a notification to the site visitor when they submit a contact form, letting them know you received their form and will be in contact shortly. This assures site visitors their form has gone through properly.</p>\n<p>For help with this step, check out our documentation on <a href="https://wpforms.com/docs/setup-form-notification-wpforms/">how to set up form notifications in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>Adding to this, if you want to keep branding across your emails consistent, you can check out this guide on <a href="https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-add-custom-header-image-in-your-wpforms-email-template/">adding a custom header to your email template</a>.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-211599" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header.jpg" alt="Custom Email Header" width="562" height="314" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header-300x168.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>When your forms notifications are configured properly, click <strong>Done</strong>.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 4: Embed Your Simple Contact Form in a Page</strong></p>\n<p>The last step in the WPForms Challenge is embedding your simple contact form in a WordPress page.</p>\n<p>WPForms is Gutenberg ready and has its very own block to help make adding forms to your website a cinch. To add a form to your WordPress page, start by clicking the <strong>Add Block</strong> button and searching for WPForms.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-397506" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/wpforms-gutenberg-block.png" alt="wpforms gutenberg block" width="562" height="553" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/wpforms-gutenberg-block.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/wpforms-gutenberg-block-300x295.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>When you click on WPForms, select your form from the dropdown menu and watch it automatically add to your WordPress page.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-397497" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/add-contact-form.png" alt="add contact form" width="562" height="410" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/add-contact-form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/add-contact-form-300x219.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>You can preview your form before publishing it on your website by clicking <strong>Preview</strong>, just like you would any time you wanted to check your content before pushing it live.</p>\n<p>When your form looks the way you want, and youre ready to make it live on your website, finish up the WPForms Challenge by clicking <strong>Done</strong> one last time.</p>\n<p>If youve completed the challenge successfully, youll see a congratulations message with the amount of time it took you to create your first simple contact form.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-397500" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/finish-wpforms-challenge.png" alt="finish wpforms challenge" width="562" height="428" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/finish-wpforms-challenge.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/finish-wpforms-challenge-300x228.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>If you want, you can even rate WPForms and share your story with others so they can see how easy it is to create a simple contact form in WordPress.</p>\n<p>Just dont forget, youll need to click <strong>Publish</strong> for your form to go live on your site.</p>\n<div class="alert alert-info">If youre still using the Classic Editor, adding your form to your website is still simple. Click the <strong>Add Form</strong> button in the Visual Editor, select your form from the dropdown menu, and click <strong>Add Form</strong>. Then publish your page so your form appears on your site.</div>\n<h3 id="create-contact-form">Create a Simple Contact Form</h3>\n<p>These step by step instructions are for those that dont want to take the WPForms Challenge, or have already done it and want to know how to create a simple contact form in a more traditional way.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 1: Create a Simple Contact Form</strong></p>\n<p>The first thing youll need to do is install and activate the <a href="https://wpforms.com/pricing/">WPForms plugin</a>. For more details, see this step by step guide on <a title="Step by step guide on How to Install a WordPress Plugin" href="http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/step-by-step-guide-to-install-a-wordpress-plugin-for-beginners/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">how to install a plugin in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>Next, go to <strong>WPForms  Add New</strong> to create a new form.</p>\n<p>On the setup screen, name your form and select the Simple Contact Form template.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-397504" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/simple-contact-form-template.png" alt="simple contact form template" width="562" height="365" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/simple-contact-form-template.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/simple-contact-form-template-300x195.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>WPForms will create a simple contact form.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-218831" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Simple-Contact-Form.png" alt="Simple Contact Form" width="562" height="372" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Simple-Contact-Form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Simple-Contact-Form-300x199.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>Here, you can add additional fields to your contact form by dragging them from the left hand panel to the right hand panel.</p>\n<p>Then, click on the field to make any changes. You can also click on a form field and drag it to rearrange the order on your contact form.</p>\n<p>Once youre done customizing your form, click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<p>Now well take a look at how to configure your simple contact form settings.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 2: Configure Your General Contact Form Settings</strong></p>\n<p>Go to <strong>Settings</strong>  <strong>General</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-218832" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/General-Settings.png" alt="General Settings" width="562" height="439" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/General-Settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/General-Settings-300x234.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>Here you can configure the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Form Name.</strong> Rename your form if you want to.</li>\n<li><strong>Form Description.</strong> Give your form name a description.</li>\n<li><strong>Submit Button Text.</strong> Customize the copy on the submit button.</li>\n<li><strong>Spam Prevention.</strong> <a href="https://wpforms.com/how-to-build-a-spam-free-contact-form-without-captcha/">Enable the anti-spam honeypot feature</a> to prevent spambots from submitting forms. This feature is automatically enabled on all WordPress forms. If you decide to use another form of spam prevention, just unclick this option.</li>\n<li><strong>GDPR Enhancements.</strong> You can disable the storing of entry information and user details, such as IP addresses and user agents, in an effort to <a href="https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-create-gdpr-compliant-forms/">comply with GDPR requirements</a>. In addition, check out our step by step instructions on <a href="https://wpforms.com/how-to-add-a-gdpr-agreement-field-to-your-sites-forms/">how to add a GDPR agreement field to your simple contact form</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>When youre done, click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 3: Configure Your Contact Forms Notifications</strong></p>\n<p>Notifications are a great way to send an email whenever a contact form is submitted on your website.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-218833" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Notifications.png" alt="Notifications" width="562" height="228" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Notifications.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Notifications-300x122.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>In fact, unless you disable this feature, whenever someone submits a contact form on your site, youll get a notification about the contact form.</p>\n<p>If you <a href="https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-use-smart-tags-in-wpforms/">use smart tags</a>, you can also send a notification to the site visitor when they submit a contact form, letting them know you received their form and will be in contact shortly. This assures site visitors their form has gone through properly.</p>\n<p>For help with this step, check out our documentation on <a href="https://wpforms.com/docs/setup-form-notification-wpforms/">how to set up form notifications in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>Adding to this, if you want to keep branding across your emails consistent, you can check out this guide on <a href="https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-add-custom-header-image-in-your-wpforms-email-template/">adding a custom header to your email template</a>.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-211599" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header.jpg" alt="Custom Email Header" width="562" height="314" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header-300x168.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p><strong>Step 4: Configure Your Contact Form Confirmations</strong></p>\n<p>Form confirmations are messages that display to site visitors once they submit a contact form on your website. They let people know that their form has been processed and offer you the chance to let them know the next steps.</p>\n<p>WPForms has three confirmation types to choose from:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Message.</strong> This is the default confirmation type in WPForms. When a site visitor submits a contact form, a simple message confirmation will appear letting them know their form was processed. Look here for some <a href="https://wpforms.com/form-success-message-ideas-to-boost-customer-happiness/">great success messages</a> to help boost customer happiness.</li>\n<li><strong>Show Page.</strong> This confirmation type will take site visitors to a specific web page on your site thanking them for their form submission. For help doing this, check out our tutorial on <a href="https://wpforms.com/how-to-redirect-users-after-wordpress-form-submit/">redirecting customers to a thank you page</a>. In addition, be sure to check out our article on <a href="https://wpforms.com/4-thank-you-page-examples-to-boost-customer-loyalty/">creating effective Thank You pages</a> for boosting customer loyalty.</li>\n<li><strong>Go to URL (Redirect).</strong> This option is used when you want to send site visitors to a different website.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Lets see how to set up a simple form confirmation in WPForms so you can customize the message site visitors will see when they get in touch with you using your sites contact form.</p>\n<p>To start, click on the <strong>Confirmation</strong> tab in the Form Editor under <strong>Settings</strong>.</p>\n<p>Next, select the type of confirmation type youd like to create. For this example, well select <strong>Message</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-218836" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Confirmation-Message.png" alt="Confirmation Message" width="562" height="290" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Confirmation-Message.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Confirmation-Message-300x155.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>Then, customize the confirmation message to your liking, and click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<p>For help with other confirmation types, see out documentation on <a href="https://wpforms.com/docs/setup-form-confirmation-wpforms/#redirect">setting up form confirmations</a>.</p>\n<p>Now youre ready to add your contact form to your website.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 5: Add Your Contact Form to Your Website</strong></p>\n<p>After youve created your simple contact form, you need to add it to your WordPress website.</p>\n<p>WPForms allows you to add your forms to many locations on your website, including your blog posts, pages, and even <a href="https://wpforms.com/how-to-add-a-contact-form-in-wordpress-sidebar-widget/">sidebar widgets</a>.</p>\n<p>Lets take a look at the most common post/page embed option.</p>\n<p>To start, create a new post or page in WordPress and then click on the <strong>Add Form</strong> button.</p>\n<p>Next, select your contact form in the modal popup and click <strong>Add Form</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-218834" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Add-Form-1.png" alt="Add Form" width="562" height="326" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Add-Form-1.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Add-Form-1-300x174.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>Then, publish your post or page so your contact form will appear on your website.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-218829" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Final-Contact-Form.png" alt="Final Contact Form" width="562" height="334" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Final-Contact-Form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Final-Contact-Form-300x178.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>And there you have it! You now know how to create a simple contact form in WordPress.</p>\n<p>If your websites contact forms need multiple form fields, consider <a href="https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-multi-part-form-in-wordpress/">creating a multi-part form</a> to prevent form fatigue and encourage people to finish filling your forms out. And dont forget to <a href="https://wpforms.com/excellent-multi-page-form-examples-for-your-inspiration/">check out our multi-page form examples</a> if you need some inspiration.</p>\n<p>And if you really want to get more information from your contact forms, without scaring away your visitors, check out these <a href="https://wpforms.com/web-form-hacks-to-unlock-customer-data/">clever web form hacks to unlock hidden customer data</a>.</p>\n<p>So, what are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful <a href="https://wpforms.com">WordPress forms plugin</a> today.</p>\n<p>And dont forget, if you like this article, then please follow us on <a href="https://www.facebook.com/wpforms" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">Facebook</a> and <a href="http://twitter.com/easywpforms" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">Twitter</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-simple-contact-form-in-wordpress/">How to Create a Simple Contact Form in WordPress</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com">WPForms</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:74:"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-simple-contact-form-in-wordpress/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2:"26";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:5;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:57:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:61:"How to Create an Interactive Form in WordPress (the Easy Way)";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:80:"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-an-interactive-form-in-wordpress-the-easy-way/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:89:"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-an-interactive-form-in-wordpress-the-easy-way/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 27 Feb 2019 13:00:04 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:6:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:19:"WordPress Tutorials";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"form abandonment";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11:"survey form";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"form conversions";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:26:"conversational forms addon";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:5;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"interactive form";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:29:"https://wpforms.com/?p=397397";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:582:"<p>Are you looking for a way to create personal online forms and boost form completions at the same time? Giving your users a way to fill out forms as though theyre having a conversation is a great way to combat form abandonment. In this article, well show you how to create an interactive form in [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-an-interactive-form-in-wordpress-the-easy-way/">How to Create an Interactive Form in WordPress (the Easy Way)</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com">WPForms</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:14:"Lindsay Liedke";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:17570:"<p>Are you looking for a way to create personal online forms and boost form completions at the same time? Giving your users a way to fill out forms as though theyre having a conversation is a great way to combat form abandonment.</p>\n<p>In this article, well show you how to create an interactive form in WordPress.</p>\n<h3>What Are the Benefits of a Conversational Online Form?</h3>\n<p>There are many benefits to creating forms that mimic actual conversations:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Easier and faster to fill out, which boosts form completions</li>\n<li>Personal and engaging for users</li>\n<li>Can be filled out using only a keyboard, which increases form accessibility</li>\n<li>Interactive nature improves the user experience</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Up until now, there was no suitable Typeforms alternative in WordPress.</p>\n<p>Thats why our team worked hard to create <a href="https://wpforms.com/addons/conversational-forms-addon/">Conversational Forms by WPForms</a> to give your users an interactive form experience while improving form conversions.</p>\n<p>So, lets see how to create a Typeforms style form in WordPress.</p>\n<p>But first, take a look at a conversation form demo to see whats in store for you.</p>\n<p><a class="btn btn-block" style="background-color: #659a17 !important; color: #fff !important; padding: 20px 25px !important; text-align: center; text-decoration: none; border-radius: 4px !important; -moz-border-radius: 4px !important; -webkit-border-radius: 4px !important; font-weight: bold;" title="Click here to join our affiliate program" href="https://wpforms.com/conversational-forms-demo/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Click here to see Conversational Form Demo</a></p>\n<h3>Step 1: Create a New Form in WordPress</h3>\n<p>The first thing youll need to do is install and activate the <a href="https://wpforms.com/pricing/">WPForms plugin</a>. For more details, see this step by step guide on <a title="Step by step guide on How to Install a WordPress Plugin" href="http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/step-by-step-guide-to-install-a-wordpress-plugin-for-beginners/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">how to install a plugin in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>Next, youll need to create a new form.</p>\n<p>You can create any number of online forms using WPForms and the <a href="https://wpforms.com/addons/form-templates-pack-addon/">Form Templates Pack addon</a>.</p>\n<p>For instance, you can create a:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href="https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-user-registration-form-in-wordpress/">User Registration Form</a>:</strong> get all the information you need from users in a simple and fast way.</li>\n<li><strong>Event Planning Form:</strong> ask all the questions you need to throw an amazing event without exhausting your clients.</li>\n<li><strong><a href="https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-job-application-form-in-wordpress/">Job Application Form</a>:</strong> turn your long and sometimes complicated job application forms into simple and easy to digest forms.</li>\n<li><strong><a href="https://wpforms.com/addons/surveys-and-polls-addon/">Survey Form</a>:</strong> stop overwhelming users with tons of survey questions. Instead, ask one question at a time and improve form completions and accuracy.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>For our example, well create a simple survey form. For help with how to do this, check out this easy to follow tutorial on <a href="https://wpforms.com/create-a-survey-form-in-wordpress-step-by-step/">creating a survey form in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>If you want to see the survey form template in action, head over and check out our <a href="https://wpforms.com/demo/survey-form-demo/">survey form demo</a>.</p>\n<p>You can add additional fields to your form by dragging them from the left hand panel to the right hand panel.</p>\n<p>Then, click on the field to make any changes. You can also click on a form field and drag it to rearrange the order on your online form.</p>\n<p>Heres what our survey form looks like:</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-397402" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-survey-form-example.png" alt="conversational survey form example" width="562" height="449" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-survey-form-example.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-survey-form-example-300x240.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>Just remember, no matter which type of online form you create, you can give it a full-page conversational form layout.</p>\n<h3>Step 2: Install and Activate the Conversational Forms Addon</h3>\n<p>Once your WordPress form is ready, youll need to install and activate the WPForms <a href="https://wpforms.com/addons/conversational-forms-addon/">Conversational Forms addon</a>.</p>\n<p>This addon is how youll be able to turn your newly created WordPress form into an interactive form.</p>\n<p>To do this, go to <strong>WPForms</strong>  <strong>Addons</strong> and find the one labeled <strong>Conversational Forms Addon</strong>.</p>\n<p>Click <strong>Install Addon</strong> and then <strong>Activate</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-397398" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-forms-addon.png" alt="conversational forms addon" width="562" height="204" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-forms-addon.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-forms-addon-300x109.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>The Conversational Forms addon is now ready to use. But first, lets take a quick look at the general form settings you might want to configure before creating your distraction free conversational form.</p>\n<h3>Step 3: Configure Your Form Settings</h3>\n<p>There are many settings to configure once youve customized your form to look the way you want it to.</p>\n<p><strong>General Settings</strong></p>\n<p>To start, go to <strong>Settings</strong>  <strong>General</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-246850" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-General-Settings.png" alt="WPForms General Settings" width="562" height="443" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-General-Settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-General-Settings-300x236.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>Here you can change things like your forms name, description, and submit button copy.</p>\n<p>You can also <a href="https://wpforms.com/how-to-build-spam-free-wordpress-contact-forms-the-ultimate-guide/">enable additional spam prevention features</a> to <a href="https://www.wpbeginner.com/wordpress-security/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">keep your website secure</a> from unwanted form submissions.</p>\n<p><strong>Form Notifications</strong></p>\n<p>Notifications are a great way to send an email whenever a form is submitted on your website.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-246852" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-Notifications-Settings.png" alt="WPForms Notifications Settings" width="562" height="228" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-Notifications-Settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-Notifications-Settings-300x122.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>In fact, unless you disable this feature, whenever someone submits a form on your site, youll get a notification about it.</p>\n<p>For help with this step, check out our documentation on <a href="https://wpforms.com/docs/setup-form-notification-wpforms/">how to set up form notifications in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>If you need to send more than one notification, for example to yourself, a team member, and your site visitor, check out our step by step tutorial on <a href="https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-multiple-form-notifications-in-wordpress-forms/">how to send multiple form notifications in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>In addition, if you want to keep branding across your emails consistent, you can check out this guide on <a href="https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-add-custom-header-image-in-your-wpforms-email-template/">adding a custom header to your email template</a>.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-211599" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header.jpg" alt="Custom Email Header" width="562" height="314" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header-300x168.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p><strong>Form Confirmations</strong></p>\n<p>Form confirmations are messages that display to site visitors once they submit a form on your website. They let people know that their form has been processed and offer you the chance to let them know what the next steps are.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-246854" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Confirmation-Message.png" alt="Confirmation Message" width="562" height="290" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Confirmation-Message.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Confirmation-Message-300x155.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>WPForms has three confirmation types:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Message.</strong>A simple message that displays once someone submits a form on your website thanking them and letting them know what the next steps are.</li>\n<li><strong>Show Page.</strong> Redirect users to another page on your website, such as a thank you page.</li>\n<li><strong>Go to URL (Redirect).</strong> Send site visitors to a different website.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>If you want to display different confirmations to site visitors based on their behavior, be sure to read up on <a href="https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-create-conditional-form-confirmations/">how to create conditional form confirmations</a>.</p>\n<p>Click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Step 4: Configure Conversational Forms Settings</h3>\n<p>Now that you have your forms general settings configured its time to configure your conversational form settings.</p>\n<p>To do this, go to <strong>Settings</strong>  <strong>Conversational Forms</strong> in the form builder and click on the <strong>Enable Conversational Form Mode</strong> checkbox.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-397404" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/enable-conversational-forms.png" alt="enable conversational forms" width="562" height="260" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/enable-conversational-forms.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/enable-conversational-forms-300x139.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>When you do this, youll see a bunch of settings that you can customize to meet your needs.</p>\n<p><strong>Form Title and Message</strong></p>\n<p>To start, give your form a title that will display for your site visitors. This is good for letting people know what your form is all about and what action you want them to take while there.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-397401" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-forms-title.png" alt="conversational forms title" width="562" height="189" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-forms-title.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-forms-title-300x101.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>Next, you can add a short message for your site visitors to see. This gives you a chance to add some additional information so people know what to expect when they fill out your form.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-397399" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-forms-message.png" alt="conversational forms message" width="562" height="239" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-forms-message.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-forms-message-300x128.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p><strong>Permalink</strong></p>\n<p>Whenever you enable conversational form mode for your online form, the Conversational Forms addon automatically creates a unique permalink for you.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-397400" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-forms-permalink.png" alt="conversational forms permalink" width="558" height="94" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-forms-permalink.png 558w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-forms-permalink-300x51.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 558px) 100vw, 558px" /></p>\n<p>You can change this permalink if you want, or leave it.</p>\n<p>Either way, this is the URL youll use in email campaigns, internal linking, and even social media posts when you want people to click on your conversational form link and visit your site.</p>\n<p><strong>Header Logo</strong></p>\n<p>The next thing you can do to customize your interactive form landing page is add a logo. Click on <strong>Upload Image</strong> and choose the image you want to add to your form landing page.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-379741" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/header-logo.png" alt="header logo" width="562" height="180" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/header-logo.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/header-logo-300x96.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>You can also remove any WPForms branding by clicking the <strong>Hide WPForms Branding</strong> checkbox.</p>\n<p><strong>Color Schemes and Progress Bar</strong></p>\n<p>One of the best things about the WPForms Conversational Forms addon is that you can customize your interactive form landing page to have a color scheme that matches your companys branding.</p>\n<p>The color scheme you choose will determine the background color of the your forms landing page and the forms buttons.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-397405" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/interactive-form-color-schemes.png" alt="interactive form color schemes" width="562" height="333" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/interactive-form-color-schemes.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/interactive-form-color-schemes-300x178.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>To make things easy on you, weve given you several great color schemes to choose from that we know will look good no matter what.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-397410" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/color-schemes.png" alt="color schemes" width="562" height="145" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/color-schemes.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/color-schemes-300x77.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>If you dont like any of the pre-set colors, you can always use the color picker and choose a custom color.</p>\n<p>You also have two progress bar styles to choose from:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Percentage:</strong> show users in terms of percentage how far along they are while filling out your form.</li>\n<li><strong>Proportion:</strong> show users how many form fields theyve completed, so they know how many questions are left to answer.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-397406" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/progress-bar-styles.png" alt="progress bar styles" width="562" height="322" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/progress-bar-styles.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/progress-bar-styles-300x172.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>Once youve configured all your conversational form landing pages settings, you can click the <strong>Preview Conversational Form</strong> button near the top to see how your form will look once its live.</p>\n<p>When everything looks the way you want it to, click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<p>And thats it! You now know how to create an interactive form in WordPress. Now people that have the unique URL or a link to your interactive form landing page will be able to view it and fill it out.</p>\n<p>If youre looking for more ways to fight form abandonment, check out this article on <a href=" https://wpforms.com/how-to-combat-order-form-abandonment-and-increase-your-sales/ ">combatting form abandonment to boost sales</a>.</p>\n<p>So, what are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful <a href="https://wpforms.com">WordPress forms plugin</a> today.</p>\n<p>And dont forget, if you like this article, then please follow us on <a href="https://www.facebook.com/wpforms" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">Facebook</a> and <a href="http://twitter.com/easywpforms" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">Twitter</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-an-interactive-form-in-wordpress-the-easy-way/">How to Create an Interactive Form in WordPress (the Easy Way)</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com">WPForms</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:85:"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-an-interactive-form-in-wordpress-the-easy-way/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"2";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:6;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:54:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:58:"How to Allow Users to Submit Images to Your WordPress Site";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:53:"https://wpforms.com/users-submit-images-to-wordpress/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:62:"https://wpforms.com/users-submit-images-to-wordpress/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Tue, 26 Feb 2019 13:00:42 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:5:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:19:"WordPress Tutorials";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11:"file upload";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:12:"image upload";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:12:"submit image";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:13:"media library";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:28:"https://wpforms.com/?p=12286";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:545:"<p>Do you need a way to allow your website visitors to upload an image to your site, without giving them access to log in? Using a simple form makes this easy for your users. In this article, we&#8217;ll show you how to allow users to submit images to your WordPress site using WPForms. Why Allow [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com/users-submit-images-to-wordpress/">How to Allow Users to Submit Images to Your WordPress Site</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com">WPForms</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:14:"Lindsay Liedke";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:7577:"<p>Do you need a way to allow your website visitors to upload an image to your site, without giving them access to log in? Using a simple form makes this easy for your users.</p>\n<p>In this article, we&#8217;ll show you how to allow users to submit images to your WordPress site using WPForms.</p>\n<h3>Why Allow Users to Upload an Image?</h3>\n<p>You might wonder when it makes sense to allow your website visitors to upload image files to your site.</p>\n<p>Here are just a few ways they can use an image upload form:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Submitting a profile photo</li>\n<li>Adding images to their guest blog <a href="https://wpforms.com/addons/post-submissions-addon/">post submissions</a></li>\n<li>Gathering testimonials of your products</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&#8230;and you can probably think of quite a few more!</p>\n<p>Having an image upload form saves you time, since you don&#8217;t have to upload images on peoples behalf. It also helps to <a title="Ultimate Guide to WordPress Security" href="http://www.wpbeginner.com/wordpress-security/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">keep your site secure</a>, because you don&#8217;t have to give all your users access to log in to your site if they want to upload images.</p>\n<p>So, lets see how to allow users to submit images to your WordPress site.</p>\n<h3>Step 1: Create an Image Upload Form</h3>\n<p>The first thing you need to do is install and activate the <a href="https://wpforms.com/"><u>WPForms</u></a> plugin. Heres a step by step guide on <a href="http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/step-by-step-guide-to-install-a-wordpress-plugin-for-beginners/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><u>how to install a WordPress plugin</u></a>.</p>\n<p>Next, you&#8217;ll need to create a new form. You can see our tutorial on <a href="https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-file-upload-form-in-wordpress/">how to create a file upload form</a> as an example to get started.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-396824" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/file-upload-form.png" alt="file upload form" width="562" height="442" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/file-upload-form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/file-upload-form-300x236.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>If you want to see the file upload form template in action, head over and check out our <a href="https://wpforms.com/demo/file-upload-form-demo/">sample file upload form demo</a>.</p>\n<p>Just remember, you can add a <strong>File Upload</strong> form field to any form so users can submit images.</p>\n<p>For instance, you can create the following types of forms using our <a href="https://wpforms.com/addons/form-templates-pack-addon/">Form Templates Pack addon</a>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Accident report form</li>\n<li><a href="https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-contest-entry-form-in-wordpress-step-by-step/">Contest entry form</a> that requires image submissions to enter</li>\n<li>Employee Information forms so you can create employee identification badges</li>\n<li>Recipe catalog form</li>\n<li>School ID registration form</li>\n<li><a href="https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-support-ticket-form-template-best-practices/">Support ticket form</a> for things like screenshots of issues</li>\n<li>And many more</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Step 2: Customize Your Image Upload Form</h3>\n<p>You can add additional fields to your form by dragging them from the left hand panel to the right hand panel.</p>\n<p>Then, click on the field to make any changes. You can also click on a form field and drag it to rearrange the order on your image upload form.</p>\n<p>To add a short description to your File Upload form field, click on the form field and make your changes on the left hand side.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-396823" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/customize-file-upload-form.png" alt="customize file upload form" width="562" height="238" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/customize-file-upload-form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/customize-file-upload-form-300x127.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>To save any images users upload to your form, go to the <strong>Advanced Options</strong> section and select the <strong>Store file in WordPress Media Library</strong> box so images save in your <a href="http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/where-does-wordpress-store-images-on-your-site/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">WordPress Media Library</a>.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-396825" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/save-images-in-wordpress-media-library.png" alt="save images in wordpress media library" width="620" height="408" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/save-images-in-wordpress-media-library.png 620w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/save-images-in-wordpress-media-library-300x197.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px" /></p>\n<p>This way, you can access images from the <strong>Media  Library</strong> menu in your WordPress dashboard.</p>\n<p>For more information about the File Upload form field, check out our <a href="https://wpforms.com/docs/a-complete-guide-to-the-file-upload-field/">complete guide to the file upload field</a>.</p>\n<p>When your form looks the way you want it to, click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Step 3: Publish Your Image Upload Form</h3>\n<p>After youve created an image upload form, you need to add it to your WordPress website.</p>\n<p>WPForms allows you to add your forms to many locations on your website, including your blog posts, pages, and even <a href="https://wpforms.com/how-to-add-a-contact-form-in-wordpress-sidebar-widget/">sidebar widgets</a>.</p>\n<p>Lets take a look at the most common post/page embed option.</p>\n<p>To start, create a new post or page in WordPress and then click on the <strong>Add Form</strong> button.</p>\n<p>Next, select your image upload form in the modal popup and click <strong>Add Form</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-396822" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/add-image-upload-form.png" alt="add image upload form" width="562" height="337" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/add-image-upload-form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/add-image-upload-form-300x180.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px" /></p>\n<p>Then, publish your post or page so your form will appear on your website.</p>\n<p>And there you have it! You now know how to allows users to submit images to your WordPress site.</p>\n<p>Want your users to be able to submit a whole blog post, instead of just an image? Check out our guide on <a href="https://wpforms.com/how-to-allow-users-to-submit-blog-posts-on-your-wordpress-site/">how to allow users to submit blog posts</a>.</p>\n<p>So, what are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful <a href="https://wpforms.com">WordPress forms plugin</a> today.</p>\n<p>And dont forget, if you like this article, then please follow us on <a href="https://www.facebook.com/wpforms" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">Facebook</a> and <a href="http://twitter.com/easywpforms" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">Twitter</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com/users-submit-images-to-wordpress/">How to Allow Users to Submit Images to Your WordPress Site</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com">WPForms</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:58:"https://wpforms.com/users-submit-images-to-wordpress/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2:"48";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:7;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:42:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:96:"Introducing Conversational Forms by WPForms  Interactive Form Layout to Boost Form Completion";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:64:"https://wpforms.com/introducing-conversational-forms-by-wpforms/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:73:"https://wpforms.com/introducing-conversational-forms-by-wpforms/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Thu, 21 Feb 2019 15:47:10 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:12:"Announcement";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:29:"https://wpforms.com/?p=391170";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:624:"<p>Form abandonment is a real problem! Majority of users who start filling out your forms leave the page before completing it. Don&#8217;t believe me? Just look at your Google Analytics. Now imagine, how many leads are you losing on a daily basis from visitors due to form abandonment? Every day you don&#8217;t act to fix [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com/introducing-conversational-forms-by-wpforms/">Introducing Conversational Forms by WPForms &#8211; Interactive Form Layout to Boost Form Completion</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com">WPForms</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11:"Syed Balkhi";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6465:"<p>Form abandonment is a real problem!</p>\n<p>Majority of users who start filling out your forms leave the page before completing it.</p>\n<p>Don&#8217;t believe me? Just look at your Google Analytics.</p>\n<p>Now imagine, how many leads are you losing on a daily basis from visitors due to form abandonment?</p>\n<p>Every day you don&#8217;t act to fix form abandonment, <u>you&#8217;re losing money</u>.</p>\n<p>Over the years, we have added solutions to help business owners reduce form abandonment and increase conversions such as our <a title="Form Abandonment Addon" href="https://wpforms.com/addons/form-abandonment-addon/">smart form abandonment solution</a> and our high-converting <a title="Form Pages Addon" href="https://wpforms.com/addons/form-pages-addon/">form landing pages</a>.</p>\n<p>Today, we&#8217;re making WPForms even better with our brand new solution: <strong>Conversational Forms</strong>.</p>\n<p>Conversational Forms by WPForms is the first true interactive form layout built exclusively for WordPress that is guaranteed to boost form completion and your overall form conversions.</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-391720" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/interactive-conversational-forms-example.gif" alt="interactive conversational forms example" width="1030" height="742" /></p>\n<p>Our goal with Conversational Forms is to help make your WordPress forms feel more human.</p>\n<p>Instead of asking all twenty questions at once, Conversational Forms takes the <strong>one question at a time approach</strong> similar to a face-to-face conversation.</p>\n<p>The full-page conversational form layout makes your form less overwhelming and more personal, leading to a <u>better form completion rate</u>.</p>\n<p>Similar to our Form Pages addon, Conversational Forms allows you to create a distraction-free conversational form landing page in less than 5 minutes (without writing any code).</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone wp-image-391779" src="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-forms-enable-mode.png" alt="conversational forms enable mode" width="620" height="451" srcset="https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-forms-enable-mode.png 1174w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-forms-enable-mode-300x218.png 300w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-forms-enable-mode-768x559.png 768w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-forms-enable-mode-1024x745.png 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px" /></p>\n<p>You can add your logo, choose a color scheme, and pick from different progress bar styles.</p>\n<p>The best part about conversational form landing pages is that your users can complete the entire form using just their keyboard similar to as if they were having a chat conversation on Messenger.</p>\n<p>This user experience also works great for smart phones (mobile) and tablets making your forms more accessible for all.</p>\n<p><a class="btn btn-block" style="background-color: #659a17 !important; color: #fff !important; padding: 20px 25px !important; text-align: center; text-decoration: none; border-radius: 4px !important; -moz-border-radius: 4px !important; -webkit-border-radius: 4px !important; font-weight: bold;" title="Click here to join our affiliate program" href="https://wpforms.com/conversational-forms-demo/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Click here to see Conversational Form Demo</a></p>\n<p>Conversational Forms by WPForms is a perfect Typeform alternative for WordPress which gives you access to all powerful WPForms features without the high costs of Typeform.</p>\n<p>You can use conversational forms to improve your form completion rate on:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a title="Surveys and Polls Addon" href="https://wpforms.com/addons/surveys-and-polls-addon/">Survey Forms</a></strong> &#8211; Instead of overwhelming people with a lot of survey questions, use the Conversational Forms&#8217; one-question at a time approach to improve your survey completion rate.</li>\n<li><strong><a title="How to Create a Job Application Form in WordPress" href="https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-job-application-form-in-wordpress/">Job Application Form</a></strong> &#8211; 60% of job seekers abandon the job application forms because they&#8217;re too long or complicated. With conversational forms, you can make your job application forms easy (<a title="101 Unbelievable Online Form Statistics &amp; Facts for 2019" href="https://wpforms.com/online-form-statistics-facts/">source</a>).</li>\n<li><strong>Event Planning Form</strong> &#8211; As an event planner, you know how many questions you have to ask clients to plan the perfect event. The step by step, one question at a time approach helps you get the data you need without tiring your clients.</li>\n<li><strong><a title="User Registration Addon" href="https://wpforms.com/addons/user-registration-addon/">User Registration Form</a></strong> &#8211; Use conversational forms to improve your registration form conversation rate.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The best part about WPForms&#8217; Conversational Forms addon is that you can turn any of your existing WordPress forms into an interactive form with a click of a button.</p>\n<p>And yes, you can use all the powerful WPForms features with Conversational Forms such as our <a title="Conditional Logic" href="https://wpforms.com/features/conditional-logic/">smart form logic</a>, marketing integrations, etc.</p>\n<p>We have literally taken the pain out of creating interactive WordPress forms, so you can focus on growing your business.</p>\n<p>So, what are you waiting for?</p>\n<p>Give Conversational Forms a try, and let us know what you think.</p>\n<p>As always, thank you for your continued support of WPForms, and we look forward to bringing you more exciting updates in the future designed to help you build better online forms.</p>\n<p><em>Syed and the WPForms team</em></p>\n<p>P.S. Dont have the WPForms Pro license? <a href="https://wpforms.com/pricing/">Click here to get WPForms Pro</a> and see why over 1 million business owners trust WPForms to create their online forms.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com/introducing-conversational-forms-by-wpforms/">Introducing Conversational Forms by WPForms &#8211; Interactive Form Layout to Boost Form Completion</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpforms.com">WPForms</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:69:"https://wpforms.com/introducing-conversational-forms-by-wpforms/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2:"23";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:8;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:54:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n			